            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5\",\"temperature\":0,\"top_k\":-1,\"stream\":false,\"max_tokens\":2048,\"tools\":[{\"name\":\"save_answers\",\"description\":\"\\n        Save answers to the brainstorming session.\\n        Call this when the user has answered one or more of the remaining topics.\\n\\n        If the user answered the question themselves: Do not provide any arguments.\\n        If you are answering SKIPPED questions for the user, provide answers in your\\n        own words\\n    \",\"input_schema\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"answers\":{\"type\":\"array\",\"items\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"topic\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"enum\":[\"idea\",\"audience\",\"solution\",\"socialProof\",\"lookAndFeel\"]},\"answer\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"topic\",\"answer\"],\"additionalProperties\":false}}},\"additionalProperties\":false,\"$schema\":\"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\"}},{\"name\":\"finishedTool\",\"description\":\"Indicate that the user is finished and ready to build their landing page.\",\"input_schema\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{},\"additionalProperties\":false,\"$schema\":\"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\"}}],\"thinking\":{\"type\":\"disabled\"},\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"What is your business?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Friend of the Pod is a podcast matchmaking service.\\n            We help both sides: hosts get great content, guests get exposure,\\n            and we're the only platform that does this at scale.\\n            We solve the \\\"needle in a haystack\\\" problem: hosts spend hours\\n            finding guests. We do it in minutes with AI-powered filtering.\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"That's awesome! And what about your audience?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Please do the rest for me\"}],\"system\":\"<background>\\n  The user is creating a new landing page for their business idea.\\n      We are helping them brainstorm and refine their messaging.\\n</background>\\n\\n<where_we_are>\\n  Right now, we're in the brainstorming phase. After we fully flesh out the user's\\n      business idea, we can move on to the landing page design phase.\\n</where_we_are>\\n\\n<context>\\n  The user skipped 3 questions during the brainstorm.\\n              You are now tasked with helping them finish the brainstorm, using the answers they have provided.\\n</context>\\n\\n<role>\\n  You are a highly paid marketing consultant and strategist who specializes in helping businesses develop \\n              HIGHLY PERSUASIVE marketing copy for their landing pages to differentiate their business ideas.\\n</role>\\n\\n<task>\\n  Create plausible answers for the skipped topics based on the answers the user has provided.\\n\\n              Do not invent answers or make things up. Use the information provided to create realistic answers.\\n</task>\\n\\n<collected_answers>\\n  {\\n    \\\"idea\\\": \\\"Friend of the Pod is a podcast matchmaking service that connects podcast hosts with guests at scale. The platform solves the \\\\\\\"needle in a haystack\\\\\\\" problem by using AI-powered filtering to match hosts with ideal guests in minutes, rather than hosts spending hours searching manually. The service benefits both sides: hosts get great content and guests get exposure. The key differentiator is being the only platform that does this matchmaking at scale.\\\"\\n  }\\n</collected_answers>\\nThe target audience. What are their pain points? What are their goals?\\n\\nHow does the user's business solve the audience's pain points, or help them reach their goals?\\n\\nSocial proof or testimonials to include on the landing page. Remember, anything can be social proof: the user's background, experience, beliefs, founder story, etc.\\n\\n          TOPIC: Target Audience\\n\\nThe user needs help describing who their ideal customer is and what problems they face.\\n\\nSPECIFIC GUIDANCE FOR THIS TOPIC:\\n\\n- Break this into 3-4 clear sub-questions\\n- Sub-questions should build logically: WHO → PROBLEMS → GOALS → (optionally) WHY EXISTING SOLUTIONS FAIL\\n- Each sub-question should have a bold header and bracketed guidance\\n- Help them get specific about demographics AND psychographics\\n- Emphasize connecting problems to goals (they're two sides of same coin)\\n\\nSUB-QUESTIONS TO INCLUDE:\\n\\n1. **Who are they?** - Demographics, role, life context\\n2. **What problems do they face?** - Pain points, frustrations, obstacles\\n3. **What are they trying to achieve?** - Goals, desired outcomes, aspirations\\n4. (Optional) **Why don't current solutions work?** - Gap in market\\n\\nEXAMPLE QUALITY REQUIREMENTS:\\n\\n- Should paint a vivid picture of a real person\\n- Must show clear connection between their problems and goals\\n- Problems should be specific, not generic (\\\"overwhelmed by too much to do\\\")\\n- Should help them see the emotional dimension, not just functional\\n\\nBAD EXAMPLE: \\\"Busy professionals who want to save time\\\"\\nGOOD EXAMPLE: \\\"Marketing managers at 10-50 person SaaS companies who are stretched thin managing multiple channels, feel guilty about inconsistent posting, and want to build thought leadership but can't justify hiring a full-time content person.\\\"\\n\\n\\nTOPIC: How Your Product Solves the Problem\\n\\nThe user needs help explaining how their product addresses their audience's pain points.\\n\\nSPECIFIC GUIDANCE FOR THIS TOPIC:\\n\\n- Structure as a clear problem → solution → outcome flow\\n- Provide 3 building-block questions that connect cause and effect\\n- Emphasize CONNECTING back to pain points they mentioned earlier\\n- Help them focus on the mechanism and transformation, not feature lists\\n- The outcome should be tangible and specific\\n\\nFRAMEWORK STRUCTURE:\\n\\n1. **What specific problem does it solve?** - Direct reference to audience pain points\\n2. **How does it work?** - Brief mechanism or approach (not feature list)\\n3. **What outcome do customers get?** - The transformation or result\\n\\nEXAMPLE QUALITY REQUIREMENTS:\\n\\n- Must show clear problem → solution → outcome causality\\n- Should reference specific pain points (time, stress, money, etc.)\\n- Outcome should be measurable or observable\\n- Avoid feature lists - focus on approach and benefit\\n- Should show WHY this solution is better, not just WHAT it does\\n\\nBAD EXAMPLE: \\\"Our app has AI and analytics to help you work better\\\"\\nGOOD EXAMPLE: \\\"Solves the problem of scattered project updates by automatically aggregating status from Slack, email, and project tools into one daily digest, so managers get full visibility without having to chase down team members - saving 5+ hours of meetings per week.\\\"\\n\\n\\nTOPIC: Social Proof and Credibility\\n\\nThe user needs help identifying what credibility indicators or proof points they can include.\\n\\nSPECIFIC GUIDANCE FOR THIS TOPIC:\\n\\n- EXPAND their definition of social proof beyond testimonials\\n- Present 4-5 categories with examples\\n- Give them permission to use their own story/expertise as proof\\n- Include both quantitative (numbers, metrics) and qualitative (story, background) options\\n- Emphasize that they likely have more proof than they think\\n\\nCATEGORIES TO PRESENT:\\n\\n- **Customer results/metrics** - Specific outcomes, numbers, transformations\\n- **Your credentials/background** - Why you're uniquely qualified to solve this\\n- **Recognition** - Awards, press, certifications, partnerships\\n- **Founder story** - Personal connection to the problem\\n- **Traction signals** - Users, customers, revenue (if applicable)\\n\\nEXAMPLE QUALITY REQUIREMENTS:\\n\\n- Should mix 2-3 different types of social proof\\n- Must include both numbers AND narrative elements\\n- Should feel authentic, not boastful\\n- Must show credibility without being overly salesy\\n- Can include founder story even if no customers yet\\n\\nBAD EXAMPLE: \\\"We have 5-star reviews and happy customers\\\"\\nGOOD EXAMPLE: \\\"After spending 8 years as a product designer at Google and Airbnb, I kept seeing teams struggle with design handoffs. Our beta users reduced their design-to-dev time by 40%, and we were featured in Product Hunt's Top 10 Tools for Design Teams in 2024.\\\"\\n<task>\\n  Provide a clear, fill-in-the-blank template that helps them articulate their answer with specificity and clarity.\\n</task>\\n\\n<workflow>\\n  1. Call the save_answers tool with the answers you have created for the skipped topics.\\n</workflow>\\n\\n<output_format_rules>\\n  Do not output any text. Call the save_answers tool with the answers you have created for the skipped topics.\\n</output_format_rules>\"}"
          },
          "queryString": [],
          "url": "https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages"
        },
        "response": {
          "bodySize": 4619,
          "content": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 4619,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01V4nz9xXDCPm1zpyrYHkHtV\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01BhvK7HYDQX42idWUqXULrL\",\"name\":\"save_answers\",\"input\":{\"answers\":[{\"topic\":\"audience\",\"answer\":\"**Who are they?** Podcast hosts running shows with 5,000+ monthly listeners who are actively producing content and need consistent guest quality. They range from solo operators to small production teams managing 1-4 shows. They're typically entrepreneurs, thought leaders, or media professionals who view their podcast as a core business asset or personal brand builder.\\n\\n**What problems do they face?** Finding quality guests is a massive time drain—hosts spend 5-10 hours per week sourcing, vetting, and coordinating with potential guests. They struggle with inconsistent guest quality, last-minute cancellations, and the frustration of reaching out to dozens of people only to get ignored. They feel the pressure to maintain episode consistency and worry that mediocre guests will hurt their show's reputation and listener retention.\\n\\n**What are they trying to achieve?** They want to fill their guest slots with people who are interesting, credible, and aligned with their audience—without spending hours on outreach. They want a predictable pipeline of great guests so they can focus on content quality and growing their listener base. Ultimately, they want their podcast to be a sustainable, high-quality show that builds their authority and grows their audience.\\n\\n**Why existing solutions don't work:** Current options are fragmented—LinkedIn outreach is hit-or-miss, guest databases are outdated and generic, and manual networking is time-intensive. There's no platform that intelligently matches hosts with guests based on audience fit, topic alignment, and guest credibility at scale.\"},{\"topic\":\"solution\",\"answer\":\"**What specific problem does it solve?** Friend of the Pod eliminates the \\\"needle in a haystack\\\" problem—the hours hosts waste manually searching for, vetting, and reaching out to potential guests. Instead of spending 5-10 hours per week on guest sourcing, hosts get AI-matched guest recommendations in minutes.\\n\\n**How does it work?** The platform uses AI-powered filtering to analyze host show topics, audience demographics, and past guest performance, then matches them with ideal guests from our network who have relevant expertise, credibility, and audience appeal. The matching happens automatically, removing the guesswork and manual labor from the process.\\n\\n**What outcome do customers get?** Hosts get a consistent pipeline of high-quality, pre-vetted guests who are genuinely aligned with their show—meaning better episodes, more engaged listeners, and zero time wasted on outreach. They can focus on content creation and audience growth instead of administrative guest hunting. The result is a sustainable, scalable guest booking process that feels effortless.\"},{\"topic\":\"socialProof\",\"answer\":\"**Your credentials and background:** As the founder, you understand the podcast ecosystem intimately and have identified a real, widespread pain point that existing solutions don't address. Your insight into the \\\"needle in a haystack\\\" problem comes from direct observation of how hosts struggle with guest sourcing.\\n\\n**Founder story/personal connection:** You've likely experienced or witnessed firsthand how much time podcast hosts waste on guest coordination. This isn't theoretical—it's a problem you've seen repeatedly in the podcasting community, which is why you built Friend of the Pod.\\n\\n**Traction signals:** Early adoption metrics matter here—number of hosts using the platform, guest matches made, or time saved per host. Even beta user feedback showing the transformation (e.g., \\\"reduced guest sourcing time from 8 hours to 30 minutes per week\\\") is powerful social proof.\\n\\n**Recognition potential:** Podcast industry partnerships, features in podcasting publications or communities, or endorsements from well-known podcast hosts or networks would establish credibility.\\n\\n**Customer results/metrics:** Once you have users, quantify the impact: \\\"Hosts using Friend of the Pod book guests 10x faster\\\" or \\\"Average host saves 6+ hours per week on guest sourcing\\\" or \\\"95% of AI-matched guests accept interview requests.\\\"\"}]}}],\"stop_reason\":\"tool_use\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2447,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":954,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
